<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">cerios</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I have been pondering begining work on a user interface/client for the emulator. I was wondering if I might get a little interplay here on some ideas.<P>My main idea is a available and dynamic no zone feature, which I have been considering a trio of technical plans for:<P>1) Having a background zone loader running, it would require almost twice as much memory as EQ, and a considerably faster proceser but would load zone data into a seperate section of data, the date that is loaded and the amount of it that is located would depend upon your reletive position on the map. ie the closer you get to a zone, the more of that zone is loaded compared to the other possible zones that could be loaded. If it were timed in proper proportion then by the time anyone reached the zone boarder, bing it would already be loaded. From there, I would have to modify zone AI so that mobs could cross and be seen, that might cause a little bit of a problem.<P>My second(its really a variation on the first) idea for no zones was simply zone crushing, dividing each zone into enough chunks that you could have 9 or so loaded at once and recenter on your present location with any paticular zone boarder was passed. Only problem with this system would be that although it would load into a smaller memory section, mobs would still be working on the old zone structure from the server and so if it did not work smoothly would possibly create an ugly lag mess at zone borders.<P>The third idea which is definitly the most technically intense would be a dynamic loading of only what the character has perceptions of, this would be very cool in that it would reduce hacking potential a great deal. Unfortunatly it would probably leave anyone who could not handle a steady 200k out of being able to use it(a sizable chunk of people).<P>Dynamically loading would require substantial video memory, and a helava lot of streaming, something I don't have alot of experience in. (currently reading many books on both video game and video programing eh)<P>Just hoping a few people might be able to expand upon my ideas, maybe add a few of your own and point out pitfalls I might not see at this point.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hoihoihoi</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">hmm, 64mb kernel in mem and 200mb eq stuff in mem...<BR>/comfort RAM</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Phantal</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Or you could do a variant ...<P>Each of the required files for a given zone are all in all, typically anywhere from 5 megs to 20 megs in size.  The largest zone (by size) that I can think of is East Wastes, which measures in at a grand total of 10 megabytes on the hard drive.<P>Now, if you load any adjacent zones into memory in the background slowly, starting with whichever zones are the closest (and keeping the zone you just left in memory), you might at most consume another 30-40mb of RAM.  I can't think of many zones that have a lot of adjacent zones.  East commons has west freeport, nektulos woods, north ro, and west commons; east wastes has iceclad, kael, great divide, and crystal caverns; west wastes has sirens grotto, temple of veeshan, and dragons necropolis, etc ...<P>Once the files are in memory, you could do some pre-world building steps on each of them, working with a limited amount of memory.  I don't know much about what is in EQ's package files, but some things that you may want to try and do is have an arranged set of textures, have the appropriate pointers associated with the textures for surfaces, etc, get everything ready that you may need, but only do it when you have extra processing time.<P>OR ... you could just convert all the package files to a new format in a pre-world built fashion, so that when loaded up into memory, it's a few short steps to build that world.<P>But then, if I was going to go that far, I'd just export all the meshes into 3ds format, export all the map geometry, import it into the Unreal engine, and try to use a REAL engine for making a game.<P>-Phantal<p>[This message has been edited by Phantal (edited 03-27-2001).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">AppleKid</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"> It's a fun idea. I for one would love to see folks training specs from Oasis all the way to Freeport.  <IMG SRC="http://www.ethernalquest.com/ubb/smile.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">NYGenXer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I will be buying a 500mhz pentium server with 256 memory soon. How would I go about setting it up as my dedicated emulated EQ system to play my other 2 computers off of? I know that right now there is no way to play the real game (no ai is available for EQ anywhere), but would it be possible to adapt another game engine for it? I can't do it personaly, but I have friends who would be willing to try to run our own LAN game. I would also need to find a working copy of EverHack, but I will do that myself later. Thanks for the help.  </FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Jafo</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Blah, it's not the loading that takes significant time, it's waiting for the old and new zone servers to sync up and do database queries about you and then tell you some stuff about yourself and your zone and the people in it.<P>You'd save maybe 5 seconds.  10 on an old system.<P>Jafo<BR></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
